Let them , disquieted with dire alarms , Aspire to win a dangerous fame in arms : Me tranquil poverty shall lull to rest , Humbly secure and indolent blessed ; Warmed by the blaze of my own cheerful hearth , I'll waste the wintery hours in social mirth
to win a dangerous fame in arms
Some kid , or lamb that wants its mother's care
idle lolling on some shady seat , Near cooling fountains
That I by absence should my Delia grieve
great Messalla shine in martial toils
my tranquil days , How would I slight ambition's painful praise
On thy soft breast might I but lean my head , How downy
who sleeps not by his fair one's side
weary , weeping eyes to close , Though murmuring rills invite him to repose
No pomps like these my humble vows
thee spare Thy heaving breasts and loose dishevelled hair

Our sprightly thought , or damp our bridal joy : We'll live , my Delia , and from life remove All care , all business , but delightful Love
